---
import BlogArticle from '../../components/BlogArticle.astro';
import FlowMap from '../../components/FlowMap.astro';
import NetworkDiagram from '../../components/NetworkDiagram.astro';
import allianceGroups from '../../data/world-cup-aviation/allianceHubs.json';
import airportHubs from '../../data/world-cup-aviation/airportHubs.json';
import fanCorridors from '../../data/world-cup-aviation/sampleFanCorridors.json';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const hubByCode = Object.fromEntries(airportHubs.map((hub) => [hub.code,hub]));
const alliancePoints = allianceGroups.flatMap((group) => [
  ...group.origins.map((origin) => ({ label:origin.code,lat:origin.lat,lon:origin.lon,color:group.color })),
  ...group.destinations.map((code) => ({ label:code,lat:hubByCode[code].lat,lon:hubByCode[code].lon,color:group.color })),
]);
const uniqueAlliancePoints = [...new Map(alliancePoints.map((point) => [point.label,point])).values()];
const allianceFlows = allianceGroups.flatMap((group) => group.destinations.map((code,index) => ({ from:group.origins[index % group.origins.length], to:hubByCode[code], color:group.color, width:2 })));
const corridor = fanCorridors[0];
const corridorPoints = corridor.stops.map((stop,index) => ({ label:stop.label,lat:stop.lat,lon:stop.lon,color:index===1?'#d99a2b':'#527ca8' }));
const corridorFlows = corridor.stops.slice(0,-1).map((stop,index) => ({ from:stop,to:corridor.stops[index+1],color:'#d99a2b',width:2.5,dash:'6 4' }));
const centralityItems = [
  {label:'Atlanta / ATL',code:'ATL',matchScore:89,note:'Host + central hub'},
  {label:'Dallas / DFW',code:'DFW',matchScore:100,note:'Most matches + central hub'},
  {label:'Chicago / ORD',code:'ORD',matchScore:0,note:'No matches; major connector'},
  {label:'Denver / DEN',code:'DEN',matchScore:0,note:'No matches; major connector'},
  {label:'Houston / IAH',code:'IAH',matchScore:78,note:'Host + alliance hub'},
].map((item) => ({ ...item, connectivityScore:hubByCode[item.code].connectivityScore }));
---
<BlogArticle title="Hubs, Alliances, and World Cup Mobility" subtitle="The tournament temporarily reweights airline network flows, making connectivity and centrality more important than match counts alone." category="Aviation Networks" date="June 20, 2026" readingTime="8 min read" tags={['Aviation Networks','Network Centrality','Airline Alliances','Passenger Flows']} image={`${base}blog/hubs-alliances-world-cup-mobility-hero.png`} imageAlt="North American aviation network linking ATL, DFW, IAH, ORD, DEN, and New York area hubs with alliance-inspired flight paths">
  <p class="lead">The World Cup does not create a new airline network. It temporarily changes the amount, direction, and timing of flow across the network that already exists.</p>
  <p>That distinction matters. A list of extra flights treats every movement as an isolated event. Network analysis asks a different set of questions: Which nodes concentrate the flow? Which connections become temporarily important? Where do many plausible journeys depend on the same hub? How does a change at one node affect paths elsewhere?</p>
  <p>Seen this way, the 2026 tournament is not mainly an aviation-demand story. It is a temporary reconfiguration of airline network flows.</p>

  <h2>The Three Global Airline Alliances</h2>
  <p>Airline alliances connect carriers into broader networks through coordinated schedules, shared hubs, and interline or codeshare relationships. For World Cup travelers, that structure can determine which gateways and connections make a multi-city journey practical.</p>
  <figure class="alliance-network" aria-labelledby="alliance-network-title">
    <div class="alliance-network-heading">
      <strong id="alliance-network-title">Alliance networks at a glance</strong>
